text:
Hi Allan, I was lucky enough to visit Japan recently and I can‚Äôt thank you enough for this video. Thank you for all the suggestions. I‚Äôve followed so many of your recommendations and everything was fantastic. 
Of all, Okonomiyaki in Okaru, Osaka was probably one of the best meals I‚Äôve had in Japan. And most important of all, Koyasan. I was blessed to have spent a night in the temple and it was an experience of a lifetime. And Okunoin cemetery was the highlight of the trip. It was one of the most serene, peaceful places I‚Äôve ever been. And as told in the video, once you cross the Gobyobashi bridge, you enter Kobo Daishi temple which has surreal spiritual energy, that cannot be expressed. A must, must visit!

text:
I'm not sure if you will read this comment given it's more than an year. I have a question... But first, let me say this video is absolute art, loved it, and I am planning my japan trip pretty much based on this itinerary. Thank you very much.
My question is:
I am planning not to buy a JR pass... Im arriving at Osaka and Departing from Tokyo. I am searching for non reserved seats trains to go between cities, such as from Nara to Kyoto, and I can see fares around 700-900 yen for a single ride ticket, does this sound right?
And also, Can i use an IC card to make the travel? as in, I tap in with the IC card in Nara, and Tap Out in Kyoto, as if I were using the metro, or it depends on the region? or better just buy the tickets at the vending machine and leave the IC Card for Metro and local buses?
Lastly I just want to ask... How on earth is it possible JR passes can be affordable? With the price increase this year, a 20+ days JR pass is more than 800usd... But single ride tickets go from 5-50usd, a shinkansen from Kyoto to Tokyo is around 9000yen, 50usd... I guess what I'm trying to say is, I find it difficult to find the JR Pass option profitable, but is it because of the price increase? or is there something else i'm not considering about buying single ride tickets? I know reserving a seat has an extra fee, but goes around 500yen for JR trains such as Nara-Kyoto. I'm a bit surprised on how cheap single ride tickets are compared the JR Pass price haha. Thank you!

text:
I visited Japan last month and it was a blast! A lot of the places we went to were because of this video so thank you for that.

One part that was a bit sad was when we visited the Senko-Ji temple. The dog completely lost its color, mostly gray now, and looked feeble with flies hovering around it. We asked the monk about the dog and he told us that it could barely see.

Also, the walking up mountains was a bit understated in the video. There are A LOT of steps and you will be exhausted, and possibly turn around before making it to the top. The journey to the top would usually be worth, but we warned of the hike up haha.

text:
I am a Japanese living in Okinawa.

There are 47 prefectures in Japan, and I think that each of the 47 prefectures has 47 different charms. That's why I love this country. In addition to sushi, ramen, and sukiyaki, each prefecture has its own traditional cuisine, traditional culture, and wonderful scenery.

For example, in Okinawa, where I was born and raised, there are many other unique Okinawan dishes such as Okinawa soba, goya chanpuru, pawpaw, and sata andagi. Also, since Okinawa was originally a single country called the Ryukyu Kingdom, it has its own culture and history. Karate is also a sport that originated in Okinawa. In terms of music, Sanshin, Eisa, and Kachaashi are famous. As you can see, Japan has more than just one attraction. I would like you to travel to Japan and find your favorite prefecture.

I translated it so there may be some wrong English

text: I am Japanese.  When you come to Japan, I think it's good to think about the season.  Especially when looking at natural scenery, the seasons are important because you can see completely different beautiful scenery such as cherry blossoms in spring, green leaves in summer, red leaves in autumn, and snowy scenery in winter.  Autumn is my favorite.  The collaboration between the yellow and orange autumn leaves and the shrine is breathtakingly beautiful.  Be careful as the temperature can vary greatly.  It would be nice to visit both the big city of Tokyo and the calm atmosphere of Kyoto and compare them.

text: Thank you Allan for this amazing video, we pretty much followed your route after watching the Iceland video and visited last June. I came across this video whilst staying in Kyoto a few days ago, I started to watch and recognized your calm voice from the Iceland video and so watched this through. (I also subscribed of course). Our next destination was Osaka, but after watching your video, we decided to go to Koyasan first. I had never heard of the place and would definitely have missed it. We went yesterday - 19th February 2023, it was was raining hard, misty and fairly cold (snow on the ground). We started with the Danj≈ç-garan temple complex and had the place completely to ourselves, the rain and mist added to the experience and was one of the best days of my life. We have travelled to over 40 countries including many over the past 9 months and Koyasan for me rates right up there with the best places in the world. We also spent a fair while at the Cemetery which was also an amazing experience that we will not forget. Thank you so much for letting us know about this place and for making such awesome videos. We will definitely check where Allan went before finalizing out itinerary in future!

Thank you for sharing! As a Japanese, I'm sincerely proud of being a part of this country and I love this country as much as I thank god to be borne as a Japanese.
To foreigners, I think Japanese sometimes may be seen to be too shy. But in such case, please be reminded of the language barrier between Japanese and English! Both are so different! 
Every time you are in trouble in Japan, please be reminded that most of Japanese are very kind and most of time glad to help foreigners who are traveling Japan. Please don't hesitate to talk to Japanese local. I as a Japanese guarantee that 9 of 10 of them will try their the best to help you.

text: I am a Japanese living in Iwate prefecture in the north of Japan.  Since there are four seasons when you come to Japan, it is recommended to change the location according to the season.  For example: Spring is the Kanto region, summer is the Kyushu region, autumn is the Kinki region, and winter is the Tohoku region.  I think spring is the best season.  You may not be able to come here for a while due to the corona virus, but there are many different cultures, so please do your research in advance and experience many cultures.  Thank you for making this video,

I spent some time in Japan, and I really enjoyed myself. On a few occasions I had the chance to meet members of the Japanese upper class. I‚Äôm not saying this metaphorically. The Japanese military has built huge underground facilities, which can hold at least a million people for years. In the event of a war, the important elderly people will be taken to safety, while the young people will be left on the surface to die. That‚Äôs not a good plan.

If the Japanese wish to restore Japan to the position of a legitimate country, then the power of the old guard will have to be broken. And there‚Äôs only one way to do it: Peacefully. Ask the Prime Minister for his emergency war plans. How will the Japanese people be fed? How much food is in storage? And finally, where are the underground cities? All of that information is critically important. There‚Äôs no need to fight. Just ask, and then ask again, and again, and again. After ten thousand refusals, the questions will be answered. For God so loved the world that He gave His one and only Son, that whoever

''For it is by grace you have been saved, through faith - and this is not from yourselves, it is the gift of God -

''What then? Shall we sin because we are not under law but under grace? Certainly not!'' (Romans 6:15)

author: @rui159

text:
It can definitely. But it depends on how much you actually plan to use it. For example, if you plan to use a lot of JR line trains + if you plan to do a Shinkansen bullet train trip from e.g.  Tokyo to Osaka and back again to Tokyo - then it would save you money. In addition, there's also the convenience factor of just showing the pass than having to always buy tickets. All in all, you want to calculate the amount of JR-line trips you plan to make against the price of the JR Pass to see if it'll be worth it to you. 

For my trip, I just found it unnecessary as we were using a lot of non-JR transportation to get around. Furthermore, this was a one-way trip from Osaka to Tokyo. No return shinkansen trip to Osaka. This made the Pass less appealing.

text:
Not sure about there being any weight limitations. But you can bring your luggage on board the trains including the Shinkansen bullet trains and regular public trains. For example, bringing a large suitcase, I saw plenty of people doing that. Personally, I just used a backpack since I don't pack much. It was more convenient when bouncing from place to place than pulling a large heavy suitcase around. In the end, it's up to you and your needs. 

You can always just use taxis each time you need to bring luggage to or from a train station to your hotel. Will cost more but may be more comfortable than dragging it through public transport during Japanese rush hour.

The no. 1 place that I‚Äôm planning to visit is the Fushimi-Inari Taisha and Google shows that it appears beautiful both during spring and autumn. author: @rin__

text:
¬†Daenack Dranils¬† English is completely different from japanese. You don't learn Japanese do you? So you are making zero effort as well. Although as a tourist it shouldn't be necessary to learn the country's language, if the people in this country don't speak it, you are forced to find an other way. Google translate works well. Japanese people aren't generally cold. If they are cold towards you, it's probably because you did something disrespectful or have no manners. As Japan's culture is very different from most other countries, learning some basic manners is very useful. The heat is dependent on where you go (Japan stretches from north to south) and when you go (as mentioned in this video summer isn't ideal). Travelling and staying in Japan, isn't cheap, but that applies for most countries. Most tourists come from Europe and US. From these places, the plane tickets can be expensive, but that should be expected. Therefore, I highly recommend staying for over 2 weeks (3-4 weeks is good) as otherwise it's not really worth it. Food in Japan is cheaper than in many places, and has a good quality. Visits to museums and other attractions are most of the time expensive but are well made and require no japanese skills. The police isn't brutal compared to the US or other countries around the globe. As it's very hard to obtain a real gun in Japan, the police will not shoot you or harm you, as long as you behave like a civilized human. Some japanese manners and rules can seem stupid to other cultures. The seemingly large amount of these rules, comes due to the highly prioritized aspect of respect and politeness in japanese culture. They aren't hard to follow, and are an additional reason to visit Japan. 
That said, I hope you learned some things about Japan, and overthink your opinion about it. Tourist life in Japan is easy and very enjoyable. Have a great day.

text:
¬†@rin__¬†  Hi.
Wow that‚Äôs exciting!! 
I went to Fushimi-inari, when I was in junior high. That‚Äôs where many red Torii- gates are. It‚Äôs such a climb, but the view was pretty and worth it! 

 I would recommend Oct-Nov, when autumn leaves are beautiful, especially if you‚Äôre visiting Kyoto(Fushimi-Inari).
Spring is also pretty because of the cherry blossoms but it‚Äôs hard to predict when it will bloom. Every year even locals have a hard time predicting when.

text:
‚Äã@daenackdranils5624 
‚Äã
Hi, another one from Japan.First of all, I feel so sorry for you that you had bad experience in Japan.
Below comments are not meant to offend you, and don't intend to say you're wrong.

1. Yes, we do HONNE/TATEMAE thing. But, never meant to hurt people.  We are very greatful to foreign people who speak Japanese and never really mind about how good they are. Because, as you said, Japanese is very difficult language for non-native and not being used in other countries. So, in my imagination, the person who said you're a good Japanese speaker, really thought you are.

2. Since most of Japanese don't speak (or not confident about speaking) English, we don't know how to tell you what you should do/not do. But yes, we do avoid those kind of situation which (we think) might get into trouble for somereason by pointing out your "wrong" act.

3. I think it depends on who you met, what you did and how you behaved. (I know some of the police act arrogant and„ÄÄoverbearing. But not Japan only thing.)
However, Japan has not very unique forbidden rules. No violence, no drugs, no overstay etc just as same as other countries. 

4. You can run, you can sit on stairs, as long as you're not bothering other people. During the childhood we kept taught that do not think like world is yours, think about others first at anytime. So, that's the basic policy of many unannounced rules and that definitely making the rule complicated and fuzzy.

Sorry that I wrote too long about every each topics, but it really means alot to me if this helps you understand a bit more of our culture, background of our behavior.

text:
I know no one need to know this but, I did 2 holidays in japan and each are 2 weeks long (just like this vid)
what I did on first time: Osaka for 3 days, Kyoto 3 days, Nara & Kobe in 1 day (kinda regret it, Kobe is super beautiful) , and Tokyo 7 days (just because I wanna go on shopping). this also includes 1 day at universal studio osaka and 1 day at disneysea tokyo. I think I wasted to much time shopping and playing arcades in tokyo, but it was fun
2nd time: Toyama (kurobe gorge) for 2 days, Osaka 3 days, Kyoto 2 days, Hakone (including shopping at gotemba premium outlet for 1 day and onsen for 1 day) 3 days, and 4 days at Tokyo

I know this will be a very unpopular opinion. I am not that fond of kyoto, it was beautiful. but maybe once is enough. very crowded, so many ppl taking picts, it is not as peaceful as I thought it would be..

my next idea: fox village, kawagoe, saitama and hokkaido

text: I have been to Japan many times but you still managed to put a few places on my list of new spots to visit on future trips. Some places I would recommend that are not on your video are Magome/Tsumago Nakasendo Trek (a 3 hour hike between these two towns on the famous trek), Nachi Falls (Japan's highest waterfall in Wakayama Prefecture), Yamadera (mountainous temple town), Onomichi (seaside town) and Hokkaido which is now accessible via Shinkansen, though probably easier to take a budget flight to Sapporo. If you're looking for day trips from Tokyo probably two of the more popular ones are Kamakura (Little Kyoto) & Nikko (mountainous temple/onsen town). Kamakura can be combined with Enoshima & Yokohama.

text: ¬†@lalinski2322¬† Listen do NOT let ANYONE convince you not to do everything ur doing right. You planning everything out and learning japanese and figuring out everything u wanna do n see when u get there. Is the way to go. Before your any where near close going figure out EVERYTHING u need to do to get there n everything u wanna do once ur there. Figuring everything out ahead of time is the BEST way to do it. Most ppl dont do that and even if they had fun theres alot they didnt get to do or see cuz they didnt plan it all out. So they ended up not having enough time or missing things like festivals and parties. I STRONGLY  advise u to go when there are festivals n plan accordingly. You will DEFF want to see the Cherry Blossom festival. My friend went n brought me back videos n pics n it WILL BLOW UR MIND AT HOW BEAUTIFUL IT IS!! I would also advise u to plan out everything u wanna n then ADD 2 to 3 more days on top of that. That will give u time to recover from jet lag when u get there. So ur first day u dont do anything but get to the hotel n relax and go over EVERYTHING!! next day start doing it all. The day before last again just stay at the hotel n relax. Then the next day go home. This will help you out LIKE CRAZY!! Getting that rest the day u get there n the last day before u leave will give u all the energy u will need n help u calm urself down. Cuz ur gonna be INSANELY hyper n ready to go full tilt. Of course it will cost extra for them 2 days. But it WILL be worth ur while. One thing I HIGHLY advise u to do is right now before ur anywhere near going go on facebook or even dating sites or forums and find a couple of ppl that live there in the area ull mostly be at. Become GOOD friends with them. This WILL help you out tremendously. It will all be 1000X's BETTER if u have a friend that lives there. They can show u around and take u out to places that tourists normally do not go to ya know off the beaten track. And there are a bunch of places u will NOT be allowed into if ur a tourist. BUT if u have a local wit u they will let u in. Outta everything I said the 2 main ones u REALLY need to listen 2 is the rest days and becoming friends wit a local. If u do those 2 things u will have the BEST TIME OF UR LIFE!!! Of course u can just tell me to fuck off. But ppl like us that love Japan so much it will make it so much fun. That ull purposely find me again just to say how great it was that u listened to me. Also if u need ANY help AT ALL wit japan or have questions just hit me up at eiacopelli@gmail.com and I'll get back to u right away. Oh another tip make sure u ALWAYS AND I MEAN ALWAYS keep ir ID n Passpost with u EVERY SINGLE TIMEBU LEAVE THE HOTEL!! if u want more advice or help just email me and I'll help u out the best I can. But even if I never hear from u again just HAVE THE TINE OF UR LIFE THERE!!! Ur payment to me for the advice will come to be Videos n pics of ur time in Japan üòÅ

text:
This is a really beautifully made video! Very detailed and the route taken is usually different from the usual Japan vistors! Nice!

Just one thing that i would like to clarify, is the transport costs USD$500 for 2 persons? That is VERY cheap looking at the places you have went! 
Of course, the most costly one would be Takayama to Tokyo, by which a LTD Express Hida brings you from Takayama to Nagoya, and a Shinkansen from Nagoya to Tokyo, that would cost about 15,000yen or about USD$140 on the cheapest route, so $280 for both. 
The next costy one would be the LTD Express Thunderbird from Kyoto to Kanazawa would cost 6490 yen or roughly USD$60, so $120 for both ~ 
The remainder USD$100 for all the other routes here and there, to and from accomodations are amazing.... 

Do get me wrong, but i feel the JR Pass would still be able to pay for itself based on the routes you had took, and it saves the hassle of getting individual train tickets~ 

Anyhow, it is a great video and i liked it! Cheers!
